{"title_page": "Ernest B. Schoedsack", "text_new": "{{short description|American film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ernest B. Schoedsack\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Ernest Beaumont Schoedsack\n| birth_date         = June 8, 1893\n| birth_place        = [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]], US\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1979|12|23|1893|6|8}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles County]], California, US\n| othername          = \n| occupation         = [[Film producer]], [[cinematographer]], [[film director]]\n| years_active       = 1915\u20131952\n| spouse             = [[Ruth Rose]]\n| domesticpartner    = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Ernest Beaumont Schoedsack''' (June 8, 1893 \u2013 December 23, 1979) was an American motion picture [[cinematographer]], producer, and director.{{sfn|Richards|1973|p=120-123}}<ref name=\"NYT chang\" /> He worked on several films with [[Merian C. Cooper]] including ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'' and ''[[Chang: A Drama of the Wilderness]].''\n\n==Early life==\nErnest B. Schoedsack was born in [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]], on June 8, 1893.<ref name=\"they shoot pictures\">{{cite web|title=Merian C. Cooper & Ernest B. Schoedsack|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/cooperandschoedsack.htm|website=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref> He ran away from home at age fourteen and worked with road gangs.<ref name=\"concise routledge\">{{cite book|last1=Aitken|first1=Ian|title=The Concise Routledge Encyclopedia of the Documentary Film|date=February 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415596428|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ay5rIWCXlLsC&pg=PA817&lpg=PA817&dq=ernest+schoedsack+biography#v=onepage&q=ernest%20schoedsack%20biography&f=false}}</ref> He went to [[San Francisco]], where he worked as a surveyor.<ref name=\"brittanica\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B. Schoedsack|url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Ernest-B-Schoedsack|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref> He grew to be {{height|ft=6|in=5}}, and his friends called him \"Shorty.\"<ref name=\"flights of fancy\">{{cite book|last1=Von Gunde|first1=Kenneth|title=Flights of Fancy: The Great Fantasy Films|date=October 2001|publisher=McFarland & Company|isbn=9780786412143|page=108|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E5oTurPZbdUC&pg=PA108}}</ref>\n\n==Film career==\nSchoedsack began his career in films in 1914 when he became a cameraman for [[Mack Sennett]]. He continued working as a cameraman in [[World War I]].<ref name=\"TCM\" /> He served in the [[Signal Corps (United States Army)|Signal Corps]] of the [[United States Army]] in [[France]] in 1916.<ref name=\"ency.com\">{{cite web|title=Schoedsack, Ernest B.|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3406801402.html|publisher=encyclopedia.com|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref> He also flew in combat missions.<ref name=\"concise routledge\" /> After the war, he stayed in [[Europe]] furthering his career as a cameraman.<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> His eyesight was severely damaged in World War I, yet he continued to work with films afterwards.<ref name=\"classic monsters\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B Schoedsack|url=http://www.classic-monsters.com/ernest-b-schoedsack/|publisher=Classic Monsters|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref> In 1920, Schoedsack helped refugees in [[Poland]] escape the [[Polish\u2013Russian Wars]]. He worked with the [[American Red Cross]]. During 1921 and 1922, he also helped refugees from the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919\u201322)|Greco-Turkish War]]. He was hired by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as a cameraman on an expedition around the world.<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n===''Chang'' and early films===\nSchoedsack began as a co-director with [[Merian C. Cooper]].<ref name=\"NYT chang\" /> He first met Cooper in 1918 in [[Vienna]].<ref name=\"concise routledge\" /> They both later worked for ''The New York Times,'' but decided to make their own films.<ref name=\"flights of fancy\" /> Their first collaboration was on ''Grass'' which was produced in 1925.<ref name=\"NYT chang\" /> That same year Schoedsack met screenwriter and former actress [[Ruth Rose]],<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> would later marry her in 1926.<ref name=\"ency.com\" /> They met on an expedition [[Galapagos Islands]] where Schoedsack was the cameraman on that trip, and Rose was the official historian.<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\nIn 1927, Cooper and Schoedsack produced the film ''[[Chang: A Drama of the Wilderness]]'' together, which depicts a man's survival in the Northern [[Siam]]ese jungle. Schoedsack and Cooper spent 18 months in the jungle in order to produce the film and photograph certain scenes.<ref name=\"NYT chang\">{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Mordaunt|title=The Screen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE0DD163CE733A25753C3A9629C946695D6CF|accessdate=June 1, 2016|agency=The New York Times|date=April 30, 1927}}</ref> While producing the film, stampeding elephants that are featured in the movie almost ran over Schoedsack and his crew. The risk was worth it, however, and ''Chang'' was later nominated Best Picture at the first [[Academy Awards]] show.<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> Schoedsack kept a print of a [[Bengal tiger]] pouncing with its jaws open in his office. When asked by a reporter about the photo, Schoedsack said that the tiger had sprung and he shot it.<ref name=\"tracking king kong\">{{cite book|last1=Erb|first1=Cynthia|title=Tracking King Kong: A Hollywood Icon in World Culture|date=April 2009|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=9780814334300|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FkMlXTDR_q8C&pg=PA65}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the duo worked to create ''[[The Four Feathers (1929 film)|The Four Feathers]]'' film. It was the first fiction film that Schoedsack and Cooper collaborated on. It was also one of the last silent films of [[Hollywood]].<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n===''King Kong'' and early 1930s films===\n[[File:KingKongStyleA.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7]]\nWhile Schoedsack and Cooper made several other films together, they are most known for directing the 1933 film ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]].''<ref name=\"TCM\" /> After finishing production on ''[[The Most Dangerous Game (film)|The Most Dangerous Game]],'' Schoedsack joined Cooper in the production of ''King Kong.'' Schoedsack focused on scenes with human actors, while Cooper headed the special effects. Schoedsack, Cooper, and Rose inspired the characters of John Driscoll, Carl Denham, and Ann Darrow respectively.<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> The script was co-written by Schoedsack's wife, Rose. This film marked a transition in the working relationship of Schoedsack and Cooper. After the film, Schoedsack only directed films, while Cooper produced them. Their partnership ended, however, in the late 1930s.<ref name=\"TCM\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B. Schdoedsack|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/171965%7C48719/Ernest-B-Schoedsack/|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Time Warner Company|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, after filming ''King Kong,'' Schoedsack worked on shooting for a film that was never completed called ''Arabia''. For this project, Schoedsack went to shoot on location in [[Syria]].<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> Another film was made in the ''King Kong'' franchise. Rose wrote the screenplay for the next film, ''[[Son of Kong]]'' which was released in 1933 by [[RKO]]. Schoedsack was the sole director of the film. Also in 1933, Rose and Schoedsack collaborated on the film ''[[Blind Adventure]].''<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n===Later work===\nSchoedsack directed several other films in the 1930s including ''[[The Last Days of Pompeii (1935 film)|The Last Days of Pompeii]],'' ''[[Trouble in Morocco]],'' and ''[[Outlaws of the Orient]]''. In 1940, Schoedsack directed ''[[Dr. Cyclops]]'' which was Hollywood's first science fiction film in [[technicolor]]. In 1949 the film ''[[Mighty Joe Young (1949 film)|Mighty Joe Young]]'' was released by RKO and was directed by Schoedsack. It was a reunion film of the main King Kong creative team of Cooper, Schoedsack, and Ruth Rose. This would be the last film that Schoedsack would direct due to eye injuries received in World War II from testing photography equipment.<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n==Later life==\nSchoedsack died on December 23, 1979 in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"classic monsters\" /> They are interred together at [[Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"geni\">{{cite web|title=Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery|url=https://www.geni.com/projects/Westwood-Village-Memorial-Park-Cemetery/18387|website=Geni|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|-\n! Film !! Year released !! Contribution\n|-\n|''The Lost Empire''||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1924|| Director of photography<ref name=\"TCM filmography\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B. Schoedsack: Complete Filmography|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/171965%7C48719/Ernest-B-Schoedsack/filmography.html|website=TCM|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Grass (1925 film)|Grass]]''||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1925||Producer, Director<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Eagle Squadron (film)|Eagle Squadron]]''||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1924|| Background photographer<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Greed (1924 film)|Greed]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1925|| Director of photography<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Chang: A Drama of the Wilderness]]'' || style=\"text-align: center;\"|1927 || Producer,<ref name=\"altoona\">{{cite news|title=Now Showing: Chang|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/57657564/?terms=Ernest%2BB.%2BSchoedsack|accessdate=June 2, 2016|work=Altoona Tribune|via=Newspapers.com|date=May 19, 1928}}</ref> director<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''Gow, the Head Hunter'' || style=\"text-align: center;\"|1928|| Director of photography<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[The Four Feathers (1929 film)|The Four Feathers]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1929|| Film editor, director, director of photography<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Rango (1931 film)|Rango]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1931 || Writer, director, producer in Sumatra, editor, photographer<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[The Most Dangerous Game (film)|The Most Dangerous Game]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1932|| Director<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1933|| Director<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''[[Son of Kong]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1933|| Director<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Blind Adventure]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1933|| Director<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''[[The Monkey's Paw (1933 film)|The Monkey's Paw]]'' || style=\"text-align: center;\"|1933 || Director of prologue<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Long Lost Father]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1934|| Director<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''[[The Last Days of Pompeii (1935 film)|The Last Days of Pompeii]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1935|| Director<ref name=\"days of Pompeii newspaper\">{{cite news|last1=Reddington|first1=John|title=The Screen: 'Last Days of Pompeii\" at the Center Theater|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/52612975/?terms=Ernest%2BB.%2BSchoedsack|accessdate=June 2, 2016|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|via=Newspapers.com|date=October 17, 1935}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Lives of a Bengal Lancer (film)|The Lives of a Bengal Lancer]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1935||style=\"width: 275px\"| Photographer and director of shooting of background location shooting in [[India]]<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''[[Outlaws of the Orient]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1937|| Director<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''[[Trouble in Morocco]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1937|| Director<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''[[Dr. Cyclops]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1940|| Director<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''[[Mighty Joe Young (1949 film)|Mighty Joe Young]]''||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1949|| Director<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n|-\n|''This is Cinerama'' || style=\"text-align: center;\"|1952|| Director<ref name=\"MUBI\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B. Schoedsack|url=https://mubi.com/cast/ernest-b-schoedsack|website=MUBI|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Mario Gerosa, ''Il cinema di Ernest B. Schoedsack'', Il Foglio letterario, Piombino, 2015 {{ISBN|8876065342}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0774325|name=Ernest B. Schoedsack}}\n* {{Find a Grave|5454|Ernest Schoedsack}}\n* {{Cite archival metadata\n|author = Finding aid author: Lucy Brimhall\n|title = Ernest B. Schoedsack sound recordings\n|url = https://findingaid.lib.byu.edu/viewItem/MSS%205792\n|repository = L. Tom Perry Special Collections\n|location = Provo, UT\n|date = 2013\n|accessdate = May 16, 2016\n}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/13/movies/MoviesFeatures/getting-that-monkey-off-his-creators-back.html?_r=0 ''Getting That Monkey Off His Creator's Back''] article in ''The New York Times'' featuring Schoedsack\n* [https://www.newspapers.com/image/128778783/?terms=Ernest%2BB.%2BSchoedsack ''Oakland Tribune'' Interview with Ernest Schoedsack]\n\n{{Ernest B. Schoedsack}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schoedsack}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:American cinematographers]]\n[[Category:People from Council Bluffs, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Iowa]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Ernest B. Schoedsack\n| image                 =\n| imagesize             =\n| caption               =\n| birthname             =Ernest Beaumont Schhoedsack\n| birth_date            = June 8, 1893\n| birth_place           = [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]], US\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1979|12|23|1893|6|8}}\n| death_place           = [[Los Angeles County]], California, US\n| othername             =\n| occupation            = [[Film producer]], [[cinematographer]], [[film director]]\n| years_active          = 1915\u20131952\n| spouse                = [[Ruth Rose]]\n| domesticpartner       =\n| website               =\n}}\n\n'''Ernest Beaumont Schoedsack''' (June 8, 1893 \u2013 December 23, 1979) was an American motion picture [[cinematographer]], producer, and director.{{sfn|Richards|1973|p=120-123}}<ref name=\"NYT chang\" /> He worked on several films with [[Merian C. Cooper]] including ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'' and ''[[Chang: A Drama of the Wilderness]].''\n\n==Early life==\nErnest B. Schoedsack was born in [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]], on June 8, 1893.<ref name=\"they shoot pictures\">{{cite web|title=Merian C. Cooper & Ernest B. Schoedsack|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/cooperandschoedsack.htm|website=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref> He ran away from home at age fourteen and worked with road gangs.<ref name=\"concise routledge\">{{cite book|last1=Aitken|first1=Ian|title=The Concise Routledge Encyclopedia of the Documentary Film|date=February 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415596428|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ay5rIWCXlLsC&pg=PA817&lpg=PA817&dq=ernest+schoedsack+biography#v=onepage&q=ernest%20schoedsack%20biography&f=false}}</ref> He went to [[San Francisco]], where he worked as a surveyor.<ref name=\"brittanica\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B. Schoedsack|url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Ernest-B-Schoedsack|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref> He grew to be {{height|ft=6|in=5}}, and his friends called him \"Shorty.\"<ref name=\"flights of fancy\">{{cite book|last1=Von Gunde|first1=Kenneth|title=Flights of Fancy: The Great Fantasy Films|date=October 2001|publisher=McFarland & Company|isbn=9780786412143|page=108|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E5oTurPZbdUC&pg=PA108}}</ref>\n\n==Film career==\nSchoedsack began his career in films in 1914 when he became a cameraman for [[Mack Sennett]]. He continued working as a cameraman in [[World War I]].<ref name=\"TCM\" /> He served in the [[Signal Corps (United States Army)|Signal Corps]] of the [[United States Army]] in [[France]] in 1916.<ref name=\"ency.com\">{{cite web|title=Schoedsack, Ernest B.|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3406801402.html|publisher=encyclopedia.com|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref> He also flew in combat missions.<ref name=\"concise routledge\" /> After the war, he stayed in [[Europe]] furthering his career as a cameraman.<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> His eyesight was severely damaged in World War I, yet he continued to work with films afterwards.<ref name=\"classic monsters\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B Schoedsack|url=http://www.classic-monsters.com/ernest-b-schoedsack/|publisher=Classic Monsters|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref> In 1920, Schoedsack helped refugees in [[Poland]] escape the [[Polish\u2013Russian Wars]]. He worked with the [[American Red Cross]]. During 1921 and 1922, he also helped refugees from the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919\u201322)|Greco-Turkish War]]. He was hired by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as a cameraman on an expedition around the world.<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n===''Chang'' and early films===\nSchoedsack began as a co-director with [[Merian C. Cooper]].<ref name=\"NYT chang\" /> He first met Cooper in 1918 in [[Vienna]].<ref name=\"concise routledge\" /> They both later worked for ''The New York Times,'' but decided to make their own films.<ref name=\"flights of fancy\" /> Their first collaboration was on ''Grass'' which was produced in 1925.<ref name=\"NYT chang\" /> That same year Schoedsack met screenwriter and former actress [[Ruth Rose]],<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> would later marry her in 1926.<ref name=\"ency.com\" /> They met on an expedition [[Galapagos Islands]] where Schoedsack was the cameraman on that trip, and Rose was the official historian.<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\nIn 1927, Cooper and Schoedsack produced the film ''[[Chang: A Drama of the Wilderness]]'' together, which depicts a man's survival in the Northern [[Siam]]ese jungle. Schoedsack and Cooper spent 18 months in the jungle in order to produce the film and photograph certain scenes.<ref name=\"NYT chang\">{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Mordaunt|title=The Screen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE0DD163CE733A25753C3A9629C946695D6CF|accessdate=June 1, 2016|agency=The New York Times|date=April 30, 1927}}</ref> While producing the film, stampeding elephants that are featured in the movie almost ran over Schoedsack and his crew. The risk was worth it, however, and ''Chang'' was later nominated Best Picture at the first [[Academy Awards]] show.<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> Schoedsack kept a print of a [[Bengal tiger]] pouncing with its jaws open in his office. When asked by a reporter about the photo, Schoedsack said that the tiger had sprung and he shot it.<ref name=\"tracking king kong\">{{cite book|last1=Erb|first1=Cynthia|title=Tracking King Kong: A Hollywood Icon in World Culture|date=April 2009|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=9780814334300|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FkMlXTDR_q8C&pg=PA65}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the duo worked to create ''[[The Four Feathers (1929 film)|The Four Feathers]]'' film. It was the first fiction film that Schoedsack and Cooper collaborated on. It was also one of the last silent films of [[Hollywood]].<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n===''King Kong'' and early 1930s films===\n[[File:KingKongStyleA.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7]]\nWhile Schoedsack and Cooper made several other films together, they are most known for directing the 1933 film ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]].''<ref name=\"TCM\" /> After finishing production on ''[[The Most Dangerous Game (film)|The Most Dangerous Game]],'' Schoedsack joined Cooper in the production of ''King Kong.'' Schoedsack focused on scenes with human actors, while Cooper headed the special effects. Schoedsack, Cooper, and Rose inspired the characters of John Driscoll, Carl Denham, and Ann Darrow respectively.<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> The script was co-written by Schoedsack's wife, Rose. This film marked a transition in the working relationship of Schoedsack and Cooper. After the film, Schoedsack only directed films, while Cooper produced them. Their partnership ended, however, in the late 1930s.<ref name=\"TCM\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B. Schdoedsack|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/171965%7C48719/Ernest-B-Schoedsack/|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Time Warner Company|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, after filming ''King Kong,'' Schoedsack worked on shooting for a film that was never completed called ''Arabia''. For this project, Schoedsack went to shoot on location in [[Syria]].<ref name=\"brittanica\" /> Another film was made in the ''King Kong'' franchise. Rose wrote the screenplay for the next film, ''[[Son of Kong]]'' which was released in 1933 by [[RKO]]. Schoedsack was the sole director of the film. Also in 1933, Rose and Schoedsack collaborated on the film ''[[Blind Adventure]].''<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n===Later work===\nSchoedsack directed several other films in the 1930s including ''[[The Last Days of Pompeii (1935 film)|The Last Days of Pompeii]],'' ''[[Trouble in Morocco]],'' and ''[[Outlaws of the Orient]]''. In 1940, Schoedsack directed ''[[Dr. Cyclops]]'' which was Hollywood's first science fiction film in [[technicolor]]. In 1949 the film ''[[Mighty Joe Young (1949 film)|Mighty Joe Young]]'' was released by RKO and was directed by Schoedsack. It was a reunion film of the main King Kong creative team of Cooper, Schoedsack, and Ruth Rose. This would be the last film that Schoedsack would direct due to eye injuries received in World War II from testing photography equipment.<ref name=\"brittanica\" />\n\n==Later life==\nSchoedsack died on December 23, 1979 in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"classic monsters\" /> They are interred together at [[Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"geni\">{{cite web|title=Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery|url=https://www.geni.com/projects/Westwood-Village-Memorial-Park-Cemetery/18387|website=Geni|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|-\n! Film !! Year released !! Contribution\n|-\n|''The Lost Empire''||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1924|| Director of photography<ref name=\"TCM filmography\">{{cite web|title=Ernest B. Schoedsack: Complete Filmography|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/171965%7C48719/Ernest-B-Schoedsack/filmography.html|website=TCM|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Grass (1925 film)|Grass]]''||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1925||Producer, Director<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Eagle Squadron (film)|Eagle Squadron]]''||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1924|| Background photographer<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Greed (1924 film)|Greed]]'' ||style=\"text-align: center;\"|1925|| Director of photography<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''[[Chang: A Drama of the Wilderness]]'' || style=\"text-align: center;\"|1927 || Producer,<ref name=\"altoona\">{{cite news|title=Now Showing: Chang|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/57657564/?terms=Ernest%2BB.%2BSchoedsack|accessdate=June 2, 2016|work=Altoona Tribune|via=Newspapers.com|date=May 19, 1928}}</ref> director<ref name=\"TCM filmography\" />\n|-\n|''Gow, the Head Hunter'' || style=\"text-align: center;\"|1928|| Director of photography<r